defs.name: MongoDbX509
defs.docs:
The MONGODB-X509 mechanism based on the usage of X.509 certificates to validate a client
 where the distinguished subject name of the client certificate acts as the username.

defs.name: Plain
defs.docs:
The SASL PLAIN mechanism, as defined in [RFC 4616](), is used in MongoDB to perform LDAP
 authentication and cannot be used for any other type of authenticaiton.
 Since the credentials are stored outside of MongoDB, the "$external" database must be used
 for authentication.

attributes.value: / The SASL PLAIN mechanism, as defined in [RFC 4616](), is used in MongoDB to perform LDAP
/ authentication and cannot be used for any other type of authenticaiton.
/ Since the credentials are stored outside of MongoDB, the "$external" database must be used
/ See the [MongoDB documentation](https://docs.mongodb.com/manual/core/security-ldap/#ldap-proxy-authentication) for more information on LDAP authentication.
/ Note: This mechanism is not currently supported by this driver but will be in the future.

defs.name: MongoDbAws
defs.docs:
MONGODB-AWS authenticates using AWS IAM credentials (an access key ID and a secret access
 key), temporary AWS IAM credentials obtained from an AWS Security Token Service (STS)
 Assume Role request, or temporary AWS IAM credentials assigned to an EC2 instance or ECS
 task.

attributes.value: / MONGODB-AWS authenticates using AWS IAM credentials (an access key ID and a secret access

/ Assume Role request, or temporary AWS IAM credentials assigned to an EC2 instance or ECS
/ Note: Only server versions 4.4+ support AWS authentication. Additionally, the driver only
/ supports AWS authentication with the tokio runtime.

defs.name: local_threshold
defs.docs:
When running a read operation with a ReadPreference that allows selecting secondaries,
 `local_threshold` is used to determine how much longer the average round trip time between
 the driver and server is allowed compared to the least round trip time of all the suitable
 servers. For example, if the average round trip times of the suitable servers are 5 ms, 10
 ms, and 15 ms, and the local threshold is 8 ms, then the first two servers are within the
 latency window and could be chosen for the operation, but the last one is not.

attributes.value: / When running a read operation with a ReadPreference that allows selecting secondaries,
/ `local_threshold` is used to determine how much longer the average round trip time between
/ the driver and server is allowed compared to the least round trip time of all the suitable
/ servers. For example, if the average round trip times of the suitable servers are 5 ms, 10
/ ms, and 15 ms, and the local threshold is 8 ms, then the first two servers are within the
/ latency window and could be chosen for the operation, but the last one is not.
/ A value of zero indicates that there is no latency window, so only the server with the
/ lowest average round trip time is eligible.

defs.name: max_idle_time
defs.docs:
The amount of time that a connection can remain idle in a connection pool before being
 closed. A value of zero indicates that connections should not be closed due to being idle.

attributes.value: / The amount of time that a connection can remain idle in a connection pool before being
/ closed. A value of zero indicates that connections should not be closed due to being idle.
/ By default, connections will not be closed due to being idle.

defs.name: max_pool_size
defs.docs:
The maximum amount of connections that the Client should allow to be created in a
 connection pool for a given server. If an operation is attempted on a server while
 `max_pool_size` connections are checked out, the operation will block until an in-progress
 operation finishes and its connection is checked back into the pool.

attributes.value: / The maximum amount of connections that the Client should allow to be created in a
/ connection pool for a given server. If an operation is attempted on a server while
/ `max_pool_size` connections are checked out, the operation will block until an in-progress
/ operation finishes and its connection is checked back into the pool.

defs.name: min_pool_size
defs.docs:
The minimum number of connections that should be available in a server's connection pool at
 a given time. If fewer than `min_pool_size` connections are in the pool, connections will
 be added to the pool in the background until `min_pool_size` is reached.

attributes.value: / The minimum number of connections that should be available in a server's connection pool at
/ a given time. If fewer than `min_pool_size` connections are in the pool, connections will
/ be added to the pool in the background until `min_pool_size` is reached.

defs.docs:
The amount of time a thread should block while waiting to check out a connection before
 returning an error. Note that if there are fewer than `max_pool_size` connections checked
 out or if a connection is available in the pool, checking out a connection will not block.

/   * `tlsInsecure`: relaxes the TLS constraints on connections being made; currently is just
/     an alias of `tlsAllowInvalidCertificates`, but more behavior may be added to this option
/   * `tlsAllowInvalidCertificates`: maps to the `allow_invalidCertificates` field of the
/   * `tlsCAFile`: maps to the `ca_file_path` field of the `tls` field

 By default, it will monitor the topology of the cluster, keeping track of any changes, such
 as servers being added or removed.

Enables writing to temporary files. When set to true, aggregation stages can write data to
 the _tmp subdirectory in the dbPath directory.

 profiler, currentOp and logs.

defs.name: FindOptions
defs.value: FindOptions { allow_disk_use, allow_partial_results, batch_size, comment, cursor_type, hint, limit, max, max_await_time, max_scan, max_time, min, no_cursor_timeout, projection, read_concern, return_key, selection_criteria, show_record_id, skip, sort, collation }
defs.docs:
Specifies the options to a [`Collection::find`](../struct.Collection.html#method.find)
 operation.

defs.name: allow_disk_use
defs.docs:
Enables writing to temporary files by the server. When set to true, the find operation can
 write data to the _tmp subdirectory in the dbPath directory. Only supported in server
 versions 4.4+.

defs.name: allow_partial_results
defs.docs:
If true, partial results will be returned from a mongos rather than an error being
 returned if one or more shards is down.

defs.name: batch_size
defs.docs: The number of documents the server should return per cursor batch.

defs.name: comment
defs.docs:
Tags the query with an arbitrary string to help trace the operation through the database
 profiler, currentOp and logs.

defs.name: cursor_type
defs.docs: The type of cursor to return.

defs.name: hint
defs.docs: The index to use for the operation.

defs.name: limit
defs.docs:
The maximum number of documents to query.
 If a negative number is specified, the documents will be returned in a single batch limited
 in number by the positive value of the specified limit.

defs.name: max
defs.docs: The exclusive upper bound for a specific index.

defs.name: max_await_time
defs.docs:
The maximum amount of time for the server to wait on new documents to satisfy a tailable
 cursor query. If the cursor is not tailable, this option is ignored.

defs.name: max_scan
defs.docs: Maximum number of documents or index keys to scan when executing the query.

defs.name: max_time
defs.docs: The maximum amount of time to allow the query to run.

defs.name: min
defs.docs: The inclusive lower bound for a specific index.

defs.name: no_cursor_timeout
defs.docs: Whether the server should close the cursor after a period of inactivity.

defs.name: projection
defs.docs: Limits the fields of the document being returned.

defs.name: read_concern
defs.docs: The read concern to use for this find query.

defs.name: return_key
defs.docs: Whether to return only the index keys in the documents.

defs.name: selection_criteria
defs.docs: The criteria used to select a server for this find query.

defs.name: show_record_id
defs.docs: Whether to return the record identifier for each document.

defs.name: skip
defs.docs: The number of documents to skip before counting.

defs.name: sort
defs.docs: The order of the documents for the purposes of the operation.

defs.name: collation
defs.docs: The collation to use for the operation.

defs.name: FindOneOptions
defs.value: FindOneOptions { allow_partial_results, collation, comment, hint, max, max_scan, max_time, min, projection, read_concern, return_key, selection_criteria, show_record_id, skip, sort }
defs.docs:
Specifies the options to a [`Collection::find_one`](../struct.Collection.html#method.find_one)
 operation.

defs.name: allow_partial_results
defs.docs:
If true, partial results will be returned from a mongos rather than an error being
 returned if one or more shards is down.

attributes.value: / If true, partial results will be returned from a mongos rather than an error being
/ returned if one or more shards is down.

defs.name: collation
defs.docs: The collation to use for the operation.

attributes.value: / The collation to use for the operation.
/ information on how to use this option.

defs.name: comment
defs.docs:
Tags the query with an arbitrary string to help trace the operation through the database
 profiler, currentOp and logs.

attributes.value: / Tags the query with an arbitrary string to help trace the operation through the database

defs.name: hint
defs.docs: The index to use for the operation.

attributes.value: / The index to use for the operation.

defs.name: max
defs.docs: The exclusive upper bound for a specific index.

attributes.value: / The exclusive upper bound for a specific index.

defs.name: max_scan
defs.docs: Maximum number of documents or index keys to scan when executing the query.

attributes.value: / Maximum number of documents or index keys to scan when executing the query.
/ Note: this option is deprecated starting in MongoDB version 4.0 and removed in MongoDB 4.2.

defs.name: max_time
defs.docs: The maximum amount of time to allow the query to run.

attributes.value: / The maximum amount of time to allow the query to run.
/ This options maps to the `maxTimeMS` MongoDB query option, so the duration will be sent
/ across the wire as an integer number of milliseconds.

defs.name: min
defs.docs: The inclusive lower bound for a specific index.

attributes.value: / The inclusive lower bound for a specific index.

defs.name: projection
defs.docs: Limits the fields of the document being returned.

attributes.value: / Limits the fields of the document being returned.

defs.name: read_concern
defs.docs: The read concern to use for this find query.

attributes.value: / The read concern to use for this find query.
/ If none specified, the default set on the collection will be used.

defs.name: return_key
defs.docs: Whether to return only the index keys in the documents.

attributes.value: / Whether to return only the index keys in the documents.

defs.name: selection_criteria
defs.docs: The criteria used to select a server for this find query.

attributes.value: / The criteria used to select a server for this find query.
/ If none specified, the default set on the collection will be used.

defs.name: show_record_id
defs.docs: Whether to return the record identifier for each document.

attributes.value: / Whether to return the record identifier for each document.

defs.name: skip
defs.docs: The number of documents to skip before counting.

attributes.value: / The number of documents to skip before counting.

defs.name: sort
defs.docs: The order of the documents for the purposes of the operation.

attributes.value: / The order of the documents for the purposes of the operation.

defs.name: Collation
defs.value: Collation { locale, strength, case_level, case_first, numeric_ordering, alternate, max_variable, normalization, backwards }
defs.docs:
A collation configuration. See the official MongoDB
 [documentation](https://docs.mongodb.com/manual/reference/collation/) for more information on
 each of the fields.

defs.name: locale
defs.docs: The ICU locale.

defs.name: strength
defs.docs: The level of comparison to perform. Corresponds to [ICU Comparison Levels](http://userguide.icu-project.org/collation/concepts#TOC-Comparison-Levels).

defs.name: case_level
defs.docs: Whether to include case comparison when `strength` is level 1 or 2.

defs.name: case_first
defs.docs: The sort order of case differences during tertiary level comparisons.

defs.name: numeric_ordering
defs.docs: Whether to compare numeric strings as numbers or strings.

defs.name: alternate
defs.docs:
Whether collation should consider whitespace and punctuation as base characters for
 purposes of comparison.

defs.name: max_variable
defs.docs:
Up to which characters are considered ignorable when `alternate` is "shifted". Has no
 effect if `alternate` is set to "non-ignorable".

defs.name: normalization
defs.docs: Whether to check if text require normalization and to perform it.

defs.name: backwards
defs.docs: Whether strings with diacritics sort from the back of the string.

defs.name: Cursor
defs.docs:
A `Cursor` streams the result of a query. When a query is made, a `Cursor` will be returned with
 the first batch of results from the server; the documents will be returned as the `Cursor` is
 iterated. When the batch is exhausted and if there are more results, the `Cursor` will fetch the
 next batch of documents, and so forth until the results are exhausted. Note that because of this
 batching, additional network I/O may occur on any given call to `Cursor::next`. Because of this,
 a `Cursor` iterates over `Result<Document>` items rather than simply `Document` items.

/ next batch of documents, and so forth until the results are exhausted. Note that because of this
/ batching, additional network I/O may occur on any given call to `Cursor::next`. Because of this,
/ a `Cursor` iterates over `Result<Document>` items rather than simply `Document` items.

defs.name: CreateCollectionOptions
defs.value: CreateCollectionOptions { capped, size, max, storage_engine, validation, validation_level, validation_action, view_on, pipeline, collation, write_concern, index_option_defaults }
defs.docs:
These are the valid options for creating a collection with
 [`Database::create_collection`](../struct.Database.html#method.create_collection).

defs.name: capped
defs.docs: Whether the collection should be capped. If true, `size` must also be set.

defs.name: size
defs.docs:
The maximum size (in bytes) for a capped collection. This option is ignored if `capped` is
 not set to true.

defs.name: max
defs.docs:
The maximum number of documents in a capped collection. The `size` limit takes precedence
 over this option. If a capped collection reaches the size limit before it reaches the
 maximum number of documents, MongoDB removes old documents.

defs.name: storage_engine
defs.docs:
The storage engine that the collection should use. The value should take the following
 form:

defs.name: validation
defs.docs:
Specifies a validator to restrict the schema of documents which can exist in the
 collection. Expressions can be specified using any query operators except `$near`,
 `$nearSphere`, `$text`, and `$where`.

defs.name: validation_level
defs.docs:
Specifies how strictly the database should apply the validation rules to existing documents
 during an update.

defs.name: validation_action
defs.docs:
Specifies whether the database should return an error or simply raise a warning if inserted
 documents do not pass the validation.

defs.name: view_on
defs.docs:
The name of the source collection or view to base this view on. If specified, this will
 cause a view to be created rather than a collection.

defs.name: pipeline
defs.docs:
An array that consists of the aggregation pipeline stages to run against `view_on` to
 determine the contents of the view.

defs.name: collation
defs.docs: The default collation for the collection or view.

defs.name: write_concern
defs.docs: The write concern for the operation.

defs.name: index_option_defaults
defs.docs: The default configuration for indexes created on this collection, including the _id index.
